const SEC_K8S = {
  id:"k8s",title:"Kubernetes & Orchestration",icon:"🎯",ib:"rgba(56,189,248,.12)",ic:"#38bdf8",
  grp:"infra",bar:"#0ea5e9",tglow:"rgba(14,165,233,.07)",
  desc:"Pods, Deployments, Services, ConfigMaps, health checks, HPA, StatefulSets, and production Kubernetes debugging.",
  tags:["Pods","Deployments","Services","ConfigMaps","Probes","HPA","StatefulSets","Helm"],
  qs:[
    {q:"What is a Pod in Kubernetes and why is it the smallest deployable unit?",d:"easy",id:"pod-kubernetes-it-smallest",
     a:"A <strong>Pod</strong> is the smallest and simplest unit in Kubernetes — a group of one or more containers that share storage, network, and a specification for how to run.<br><br><strong>Key characteristics:</strong><ul><li>Containers in a Pod share the same IP address and port space</li><li>They can communicate via <code>localhost</code></li><li>They share mounted volumes</li><li>Scheduled together on the same node</li><li>Scaled and managed as a single unit</li></ul><br><strong>Why Pods, not containers?</strong> Kubernetes abstracts away container runtimes (Docker, containerd, CRI-O). Pods represent a cohesive application unit (e.g., app container + sidecar logging container).<br><br><strong>Single-container Pods</strong> are most common (90% of cases).<br><br><strong>Multi-container Pods</strong> use cases:<ul><li><strong>Sidecar:</strong> logging agent, proxy (Envoy), metrics collector</li><li><strong>Adapter:</strong> normalize monitoring data from legacy apps</li><li><strong>Ambassador:</strong> proxy to external services</li></ul><br><strong>Example:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nmetadata:\n  name: my-app\nspec:\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0\n    ports:\n    - containerPort: 8080</pre>"},

    {q:"Explain the difference between a Deployment and a StatefulSet. When would you use each?",d:"medium",id:"deployment-statefulset-would-you",
     a:"Both manage replicated Pods, but they differ in how they handle identity, storage, and ordering.<br><br><strong>Deployment (stateless applications):</strong><ul><li>Pods are <em>interchangeable</em> — no unique identity</li><li>Pod names are random: <code>myapp-7d4f8c9b-xk2p4</code></li><li>Can be killed/restarted in any order</li><li>No guaranteed network identity or persistent storage per pod</li><li>Rolling updates by default</li><li><strong>Use for:</strong> stateless web apps, APIs, microservices</li></ul><br><strong>StatefulSet (stateful applications):</strong><ul><li>Each Pod has a <em>stable, unique identity</em></li><li>Pod names are predictable: <code>mydb-0</code>, <code>mydb-1</code>, <code>mydb-2</code></li><li>Ordered, graceful deployment and scaling (0 → 1 → 2)</li><li>Ordered, graceful termination (2 → 1 → 0)</li><li>Each Pod gets its own <code>PersistentVolumeClaim</code> that persists across restarts</li><li>Stable network identity via headless Service</li><li><strong>Use for:</strong> databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, MongoDB), Kafka, Elasticsearch, ZooKeeper</li></ul><br><strong>Example — StatefulSet for PostgreSQL:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: StatefulSet\nmetadata:\n  name: postgres\nspec:\n  serviceName: \"postgres\"\n  replicas: 3\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: postgres\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: postgres\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: postgres\n        image: postgres:15\n        volumeMounts:\n        - name: data\n          mountPath: /var/lib/postgresql/data\n  volumeClaimTemplates:\n  - metadata:\n      name: data\n    spec:\n      accessModes: [\"ReadWriteOnce\"]\n      resources:\n        requests:\n          storage: 10Gi</pre><br><strong>When StatefulSet is overkill:</strong> If your app only needs shared storage (not per-pod), use a Deployment with a single PVC."},

    {q:"What are the different types of Kubernetes Services and when do you use each?",d:"medium",id:"different-types-kubernetes-services",
     a:"Services provide stable networking and load balancing for Pods. Four types:<br><br><strong>1. ClusterIP (default):</strong><ul><li>Exposes the Service on an internal cluster IP</li><li>Only accessible from within the cluster</li><li>Use for: internal microservice communication</li><li>DNS: <code>my-service.my-namespace.svc.cluster.local</code></li></ul><br><strong>2. NodePort:</strong><ul><li>Exposes the Service on each Node's IP at a static port (30000-32767)</li><li>Accessible from outside: <code>NodeIP:NodePort</code></li><li>Use for: development, testing, or when LoadBalancer isn't available</li><li>Not recommended for production (exposes nodes directly)</li></ul><br><strong>3. LoadBalancer:</strong><ul><li>Provisions an external load balancer (AWS ELB, GCP LB, Azure LB)</li><li>Automatically creates a NodePort and ClusterIP</li><li>Use for: exposing a service to the internet in cloud environments</li><li>Each LoadBalancer service gets its own public IP (can be expensive)</li></ul><br><strong>4. ExternalName:</strong><ul><li>Maps a Service to a DNS name (e.g., <code>database.example.com</code>)</li><li>No proxying, just DNS CNAME record</li><li>Use for: accessing external services with k8s DNS</li></ul><br><strong>Example — ClusterIP Service:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: Service\nmetadata:\n  name: backend-api\nspec:\n  type: ClusterIP\n  selector:\n    app: backend\n  ports:\n  - protocol: TCP\n    port: 80\n    targetPort: 8080</pre><br><strong>Modern approach:</strong> Use <strong>Ingress</strong> instead of LoadBalancer for HTTP/HTTPS traffic — one Ingress controller can handle multiple services with path/host-based routing, TLS termination, and costs less."},

    {q:"What are liveness, readiness, and startup probes? How do they differ?",d:"medium",id:"liveness-readiness-startup-probes",
     a:"Health checks (probes) tell Kubernetes whether a container is healthy and ready to serve traffic.<br><br><strong>1. Liveness Probe:</strong><ul><li>Checks if the container is <em>still running</em></li><li>If it fails → Kubernetes <strong>restarts</strong> the container</li><li>Use for: detecting deadlocks, infinite loops, or unresponsive apps</li><li>Example: HTTP <code>GET /health</code> returns 200 = healthy</li></ul><br><strong>2. Readiness Probe:</strong><ul><li>Checks if the container is <em>ready to serve traffic</em></li><li>If it fails → Kubernetes <strong>removes</strong> the Pod from the Service endpoints (no traffic sent)</li><li>Does NOT restart the container</li><li>Use for: waiting for dependencies (database, cache) to be ready, or during rolling updates</li></ul><br><strong>3. Startup Probe (Kubernetes 1.16+):</strong><ul><li>Checks if the application has <em>finished starting</em></li><li>Disables liveness/readiness checks until startup succeeds</li><li>If it fails → Kubernetes <strong>restarts</strong> the container</li><li>Use for: slow-starting apps (30+ seconds) to avoid premature restarts</li></ul><br><strong>Probe types:</strong><ol><li><strong>HTTP GET:</strong> <code>httpGet: {path: /health, port: 8080}</code></li><li><strong>TCP Socket:</strong> <code>tcpSocket: {port: 8080}</code></li><li><strong>Exec command:</strong> <code>exec: {command: [\"cat\", \"/tmp/healthy\"]}</code></li></ol><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Liveness: lightweight check (don't check dependencies — you'll cause cascading failures)</li><li>Readiness: check dependencies (database, downstream services)</li><li>Startup: use for slow apps; set long <code>failureThreshold</code></li></ul><br><strong>Example — Spring Boot app:</strong><br><pre>livenessProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /actuator/health/liveness\n    port: 8080\n  initialDelaySeconds: 30\n  periodSeconds: 10\nreadinessProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /actuator/health/readiness\n    port: 8080\n  initialDelaySeconds: 10\n  periodSeconds: 5</pre>"},

    {q:"How does Kubernetes implement zero-downtime deployments?",d:"hard",id:"kubernetes-implement-zero-downtime",
     a:"Kubernetes uses <strong>rolling updates</strong> to replace old Pods with new ones gradually, ensuring availability throughout the deployment.<br><br><strong>Rolling update strategy (default for Deployments):</strong><ol><li>Create new Pods with the new image</li><li>Wait for new Pods to pass readiness checks</li><li>Terminate old Pods</li><li>Repeat until all replicas are updated</li></ol><br><strong>Key parameters:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  strategy:\n    type: RollingUpdate\n    rollingUpdate:\n      maxUnavailable: 1   # max pods down during update\n      maxSurge: 1         # max extra pods created</pre><ul><li><code>maxUnavailable: 1</code> → at most 1 Pod unavailable (99% available for 10 replicas)</li><li><code>maxSurge: 1</code> → at most 1 extra Pod created (controls resource burst)</li></ul><br><strong>How it guarantees zero downtime:</strong><ol><li><strong>Readiness gates:</strong> new Pods must pass readiness probe before receiving traffic</li><li><strong>Service endpoint updates:</strong> only ready Pods are added to Service endpoints</li><li><strong>Connection draining:</strong> old Pods receive SIGTERM → graceful shutdown period (default 30s) → SIGKILL</li><li><strong>PreStop hook:</strong> optional delay before SIGTERM to let load balancers de-register</li></ol><br><strong>Example — Spring Boot graceful shutdown:</strong><br><pre>lifecycle:\n  preStop:\n    exec:\n      command: [\"/bin/sh\", \"-c\", \"sleep 10\"]\nterminationGracePeriodSeconds: 60</pre><br><strong>Rollback on failure:</strong> If new Pods fail readiness checks, the deployment pauses automatically. Rollback with:<br><pre>kubectl rollout undo deployment/my-app</pre><br><strong>Alternatives:</strong><ul><li><strong>Recreate:</strong> delete all old Pods, then create new ones (downtime)</li><li><strong>Blue-Green:</strong> deploy new version, then switch traffic (requires Ingress/Service mesh)</li><li><strong>Canary:</strong> deploy to a small % of users first (requires Ingress/Service mesh)</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is a ConfigMap and how is it different from a Secret?",d:"easy",id:"configmap-it-different-from",
     a:"Both <strong>ConfigMap</strong> and <strong>Secret</strong> are used to externalize configuration from container images, but they differ in security and usage.<br><br><strong>ConfigMap:</strong><ul><li>Stores <em>non-sensitive</em> configuration data as key-value pairs</li><li>Plain text storage</li><li>Use for: app config, feature flags, environment-specific settings</li><li>Max size: 1MB per ConfigMap</li></ul><br><strong>Example — ConfigMap:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: ConfigMap\nmetadata:\n  name: app-config\ndata:\n  database.url: \"jdbc:postgresql://db:5432/mydb\"\n  log.level: \"INFO\"</pre><br><strong>Secret:</strong><ul><li>Stores <em>sensitive</em> data (passwords, tokens, keys)</li><li>Base64-encoded (not encrypted by default!)</li><li>Encrypted at rest if <code>EncryptionConfiguration</code> is enabled</li><li>Not logged by kubectl</li><li>Use for: database passwords, API keys, TLS certificates</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Secret:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: Secret\nmetadata:\n  name: db-secret\ntype: Opaque\ndata:\n  username: YWRtaW4=        # base64(\"admin\")\n  password: cGFzc3dvcmQ=    # base64(\"password\")</pre><br><strong>Mounting in Pods:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0\n    env:\n    - name: DB_URL\n      valueFrom:\n        configMapKeyRef:\n          name: app-config\n          key: database.url\n    - name: DB_PASSWORD\n      valueFrom:\n        secretKeyRef:\n          name: db-secret\n          key: password</pre><br><strong>Security note:</strong> Secrets in Kubernetes are NOT secure by default (base64 is not encryption). For production:<ul><li>Enable encryption at rest</li><li>Use external secret managers (AWS Secrets Manager, Vault, Sealed Secrets)</li><li>Restrict RBAC access to Secrets</li></ul>"},

    {q:"Explain Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA). What metrics can it use?",d:"medium",id:"horizontal-pod-autoscaler-hpa",
     a:"<strong>HPA</strong> automatically scales the number of Pods based on observed metrics (CPU, memory, custom metrics).<br><br><strong>How it works:</strong><ol><li>HPA controller checks metrics every 15 seconds (default)</li><li>Calculates desired replica count: <code>desired = current × (currentMetric / targetMetric)</code></li><li>Updates the Deployment/StatefulSet replica count</li><li>Respects <code>minReplicas</code> and <code>maxReplicas</code></li></ol><br><strong>Example — CPU-based HPA:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: autoscaling/v2\nkind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler\nmetadata:\n  name: myapp-hpa\nspec:\n  scaleTargetRef:\n    apiVersion: apps/v1\n    kind: Deployment\n    name: myapp\n  minReplicas: 2\n  maxReplicas: 10\n  metrics:\n  - type: Resource\n    resource:\n      name: cpu\n      target:\n        type: Utilization\n        averageUtilization: 70  # target 70% CPU</pre><br><strong>Metric types:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Resource metrics (CPU, memory):</strong><br>Requires resource requests defined:<br><pre>resources:\n  requests:\n    cpu: \"500m\"\n    memory: \"512Mi\"</pre><br><strong>2. Custom metrics (Prometheus, Datadog):</strong><br>Example: scale based on request rate, queue depth, response time<br><pre>- type: Pods\n  pods:\n    metric:\n      name: http_requests_per_second\n    target:\n      type: AverageValue\n      averageValue: \"1000\"</pre><br><strong>3. External metrics (SQS queue length, Kafka lag):</strong><br><pre>- type: External\n  external:\n    metric:\n      name: sqs_queue_depth\n    target:\n      type: Value\n      value: \"30\"</pre><br><strong>Cooldown periods:</strong><ul><li><code>--horizontal-pod-autoscaler-downscale-stabilization=5m</code> (default) — prevents flapping</li><li>Scale-up is immediate; scale-down waits 5 minutes</li></ul><br><strong>Limitations:</strong><ul><li>Can't scale to zero (use <strong>KEDA</strong> for event-driven autoscaling)</li><li>CPU/memory-based scaling lags (reactive, not predictive)</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is a PersistentVolume (PV) and PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)?",d:"medium",id:"persistentvolume-pv-persistentvolumeclai",
     a:"Kubernetes separates <em>storage provisioning</em> (PV) from <em>storage consumption</em> (PVC) to decouple infrastructure from application needs.<br><br><strong>PersistentVolume (PV):</strong><ul><li>A piece of storage in the cluster (provisioned by admin or dynamically)</li><li>Cluster-level resource (not namespaced)</li><li>Backed by: NFS, AWS EBS, GCP Persistent Disk, Azure Disk, local disk, etc.</li><li>Has a <code>capacity</code>, <code>accessModes</code>, and <code>storageClassName</code></li></ul><br><strong>PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC):</strong><ul><li>A request for storage by a user</li><li>Namespace-scoped</li><li>Specifies: size, access mode, storage class</li><li>Kubernetes binds PVC to a matching PV</li></ul><br><strong>Access Modes:</strong><ul><li><code>ReadWriteOnce (RWO)</code> — mounted by one node (most common)</li><li><code>ReadOnlyMany (ROX)</code> — mounted read-only by many nodes</li><li><code>ReadWriteMany (RWX)</code> — mounted read-write by many nodes (needs NFS or similar)</li></ul><br><strong>Static vs Dynamic Provisioning:</strong><br><br><strong>Static:</strong> Admin creates PVs manually; users create PVCs that bind to them.<br><br><strong>Dynamic:</strong> When a PVC is created, Kubernetes automatically provisions a PV using a <code>StorageClass</code>.<br><br><strong>Example — StorageClass (AWS EBS):</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: storage.k8s.io/v1\nkind: StorageClass\nmetadata:\n  name: fast\nprovisioner: kubernetes.io/aws-ebs\nparameters:\n  type: gp3\n  iops: \"3000\"</pre><br><strong>Example — PVC:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: PersistentVolumeClaim\nmetadata:\n  name: db-pvc\nspec:\n  accessModes:\n  - ReadWriteOnce\n  storageClassName: fast\n  resources:\n    requests:\n      storage: 10Gi</pre><br><strong>Example — Pod using PVC:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  containers:\n  - name: postgres\n    image: postgres:15\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: data\n      mountPath: /var/lib/postgresql/data\n  volumes:\n  - name: data\n    persistentVolumeClaim:\n      claimName: db-pvc</pre><br><strong>Lifecycle:</strong> PVC bound to PV → Pod uses PVC → Pod deleted → PVC still exists → PV can be <code>Retain</code> (manual cleanup), <code>Delete</code> (auto-delete), or <code>Recycle</code> (deprecated)."},

    {q:"What is a DaemonSet and when would you use it?",d:"easy",id:"daemonset-would-you-use",
     a:"A <strong>DaemonSet</strong> ensures that a copy of a Pod runs on <em>every node</em> (or a subset of nodes) in the cluster.<br><br><strong>Key characteristics:</strong><ul><li>Automatically adds Pods to new nodes</li><li>Removes Pods when nodes are removed</li><li>Bypasses the scheduler (Pods are placed immediately)</li><li>One Pod per node (no replicas parameter)</li></ul><br><strong>Common use cases:</strong><ol><li><strong>Log collection:</strong> Fluentd, Filebeat on every node</li><li><strong>Monitoring agents:</strong> Prometheus Node Exporter, Datadog agent</li><li><strong>Networking:</strong> kube-proxy, CNI plugins (Calico, Weave)</li><li><strong>Security:</strong> Falco (runtime security)</li><li><strong>Storage:</strong> Ceph, Gluster storage daemons</li></ol><br><strong>Example — Fluentd logging DaemonSet:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: DaemonSet\nmetadata:\n  name: fluentd\nspec:\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: fluentd\n  template:\n    metadata:\n      labels:\n        app: fluentd\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: fluentd\n        image: fluent/fluentd:v1.14\n        volumeMounts:\n        - name: varlog\n          mountPath: /var/log\n      volumes:\n      - name: varlog\n        hostPath:\n          path: /var/log</pre><br><strong>Node selection:</strong> Use <code>nodeSelector</code> or <code>affinity</code> to run only on specific nodes (e.g., only on GPU nodes):<br><pre>spec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      nodeSelector:\n        disktype: ssd</pre><br><strong>vs Deployment:</strong> Deployment scales based on replicas; DaemonSet scales based on nodes."},

    {q:"What is the role of the kube-proxy component?",d:"medium",id:"role-kube-proxy-component",
     a:"<strong>kube-proxy</strong> is a network proxy that runs on each node and implements the Kubernetes Service abstraction by maintaining network rules for Pod-to-Service communication.<br><br><strong>What it does:</strong><ul><li>Watches the API server for Service and Endpoint changes</li><li>Programs network rules (iptables, IPVS, or eBPF) to route traffic to Service backends (Pods)</li><li>Enables load balancing across Pods behind a Service</li></ul><br><strong>Three modes:</strong><br><br><strong>1. iptables mode (default):</strong><ul><li>Creates iptables rules for each Service</li><li>Random load balancing</li><li>Low resource usage but doesn't scale well (1000+ Services = 10,000+ rules)</li></ul><br><strong>2. IPVS mode:</strong><ul><li>Uses Linux kernel IPVS (IP Virtual Server)</li><li>Better performance and scalability (supports 10,000+ Services)</li><li>Multiple load balancing algorithms: round-robin, least connections, etc.</li><li>Requires IPVS kernel modules</li></ul><br><strong>3. userspace mode (legacy, deprecated):</strong><ul><li>kube-proxy acts as a userspace proxy</li><li>Higher latency (userspace → kernel → userspace)</li></ul><br><strong>Example traffic flow:</strong><ol><li>Pod A wants to call <code>backend-service:80</code></li><li>DNS resolves to the Service ClusterIP (e.g., <code>10.96.0.10</code>)</li><li>kube-proxy iptables rule intercepts traffic to <code>10.96.0.10:80</code></li><li>Traffic is load-balanced to one of the backend Pods (e.g., <code>10.244.1.5:8080</code>)</li></ol><br><strong>Modern alternative — eBPF (Cilium):</strong> Some CNI plugins bypass kube-proxy entirely and use eBPF for faster, more efficient routing."},

    {q:"What is a Namespace in Kubernetes and why would you use multiple namespaces?",d:"easy",id:"namespace-kubernetes-would-you",
     a:"A <strong>Namespace</strong> is a virtual cluster within a physical Kubernetes cluster, providing scope for resource names and a way to divide cluster resources between multiple users or teams.<br><br><strong>Default namespaces:</strong><ul><li><code>default</code> — default for objects with no namespace</li><li><code>kube-system</code> — for system components (kube-dns, kube-proxy, etc.)</li><li><code>kube-public</code> — publicly readable, rarely used</li><li><code>kube-node-lease</code> — node heartbeat data (Kubernetes 1.14+)</li></ul><br><strong>Why use multiple namespaces?</strong><ol><li><strong>Environment separation:</strong> <code>dev</code>, <code>staging</code>, <code>production</code></li><li><strong>Team isolation:</strong> <code>team-frontend</code>, <code>team-backend</code></li><li><strong>Resource quotas:</strong> limit CPU/memory per namespace</li><li><strong>RBAC:</strong> control who can access what</li><li><strong>Network policies:</strong> isolate traffic between namespaces</li></ol><br><strong>Creating a namespace:</strong><br><pre>kubectl create namespace production</pre><br><strong>Deploying to a namespace:</strong><br><pre>kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml -n production</pre><br><strong>Resource Quotas:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: ResourceQuota\nmetadata:\n  name: compute-quota\n  namespace: dev\nspec:\n  hard:\n    requests.cpu: \"10\"\n    requests.memory: 20Gi\n    persistentvolumeclaims: \"5\"</pre><br><strong>Cross-namespace communication:</strong><br>Services are accessible via DNS: <code>service-name.namespace.svc.cluster.local</code><br><br><strong>Note:</strong> Not all resources are namespaced — Nodes, PersistentVolumes, StorageClasses are cluster-wide."},

    {q:"What is an Ingress and how does it differ from a Service?",d:"medium",id:"ingress-it-differ-from",
     a:"<strong>Service</strong> provides internal networking and load balancing. <strong>Ingress</strong> provides HTTP/HTTPS routing from outside the cluster to Services inside, with features like path-based routing, TLS termination, and virtual hosts.<br><br><strong>Service (Layer 4 — TCP/UDP):</strong><ul><li>Routes traffic to Pods based on IP and port</li><li>LoadBalancer Service = one external IP per Service (expensive)</li></ul><br><strong>Ingress (Layer 7 — HTTP/HTTPS):</strong><ul><li>Single entry point for multiple Services</li><li>Path-based routing: <code>/api</code> → backend, <code>/web</code> → frontend</li><li>Host-based routing: <code>api.example.com</code> → backend, <code>www.example.com</code> → frontend</li><li>TLS/SSL termination</li><li>URL rewriting, redirects</li></ul><br><strong>Requires an Ingress Controller:</strong><ul><li>NGINX Ingress Controller (most common)</li><li>Traefik, HAProxy, AWS ALB Ingress Controller, Google Cloud Load Balancer, Istio, Kong</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Ingress with path-based routing:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1\nkind: Ingress\nmetadata:\n  name: app-ingress\nspec:\n  rules:\n  - host: example.com\n    http:\n      paths:\n      - path: /api\n        pathType: Prefix\n        backend:\n          service:\n            name: backend-service\n            port:\n              number: 80\n      - path: /\n        pathType: Prefix\n        backend:\n          service:\n            name: frontend-service\n            port:\n              number: 80</pre><br><strong>TLS termination:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  tls:\n  - hosts:\n    - example.com\n    secretName: tls-secret</pre><br><strong>Why Ingress > LoadBalancer Services:</strong><ul><li>Cost: one load balancer for multiple services</li><li>Centralized TLS management</li><li>Advanced routing (path, host, headers)</li></ul>"},

    {q:"How does Kubernetes handle rolling updates and rollbacks?",d:"medium",id:"kubernetes-handle-rolling-updates",
     a:"Kubernetes tracks deployment history and provides built-in rollout management.<br><br><strong>Rolling Update Process:</strong><ol><li>Change the Deployment spec (e.g., new image version)</li><li>Kubernetes creates a new ReplicaSet with the new spec</li><li>Gradually scales up new ReplicaSet, scales down old ReplicaSet</li><li>Controlled by <code>maxUnavailable</code> and <code>maxSurge</code></li></ol><br><strong>Triggering a rollout:</strong><br><pre>kubectl set image deployment/myapp myapp=myapp:2.0\n# or\nkubectl apply -f deployment.yaml</pre><br><strong>Monitoring rollout status:</strong><br><pre>kubectl rollout status deployment/myapp</pre><br><strong>Viewing rollout history:</strong><br><pre>kubectl rollout history deployment/myapp\n# Shows REVISION, CHANGE-CAUSE for each deployment</pre><br><strong>Pausing a rollout:</strong><br><pre>kubectl rollout pause deployment/myapp</pre>Useful for making multiple changes before resuming.<br><br><strong>Rolling back:</strong><br><pre># Rollback to previous version\nkubectl rollout undo deployment/myapp\n\n# Rollback to a specific revision\nkubectl rollout undo deployment/myapp --to-revision=3</pre><br><strong>How rollback works:</strong><ul><li>Kubernetes keeps old ReplicaSets (default: 10 revisions)</li><li>Rollback scales up the old ReplicaSet, scales down the current one</li><li>Same rolling update strategy applies</li></ul><br><strong>Rollout configuration:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  revisionHistoryLimit: 10  # number of old ReplicaSets to keep\n  progressDeadlineSeconds: 600  # rollout fails if not progressing after 10min</pre><br><strong>Automatic rollback on failure:</strong> If new Pods fail readiness checks, the rollout pauses automatically (doesn't auto-rollback). You must manually undo or fix the issue."},

    {q:"What is RBAC in Kubernetes and how do you restrict access to resources?",d:"hard",id:"rbac-kubernetes-you-restrict",
     a:"<strong>RBAC</strong> (Role-Based Access Control) controls who can perform what actions on which resources in Kubernetes.<br><br><strong>Four key resource types:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Role:</strong> grants permissions within a <em>namespace</em><br><pre>apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1\nkind: Role\nmetadata:\n  namespace: production\n  name: pod-reader\nrules:\n- apiGroups: [\"\"]\n  resources: [\"pods\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\", \"watch\"]</pre><br><strong>2. ClusterRole:</strong> grants permissions <em>cluster-wide</em> (all namespaces + cluster resources like nodes)<br><pre>apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1\nkind: ClusterRole\nmetadata:\n  name: secret-reader\nrules:\n- apiGroups: [\"\"]\n  resources: [\"secrets\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\"]</pre><br><strong>3. RoleBinding:</strong> grants a Role to a user/group/ServiceAccount within a namespace<br><pre>apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1\nkind: RoleBinding\nmetadata:\n  name: read-pods\n  namespace: production\nsubjects:\n- kind: User\n  name: jane\n  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io\nroleRef:\n  kind: Role\n  name: pod-reader\n  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io</pre><br><strong>4. ClusterRoleBinding:</strong> grants a ClusterRole cluster-wide<br><br><strong>Verbs (actions):</strong> <code>get</code>, <code>list</code>, <code>watch</code>, <code>create</code>, <code>update</code>, <code>patch</code>, <code>delete</code>, <code>deletecollection</code><br><br><strong>ServiceAccounts:</strong> Pods run as a ServiceAccount (default: <code>default</code> SA in each namespace). Assign custom SA for fine-grained access:<br><pre>spec:\n  serviceAccountName: my-app-sa</pre><br><strong>Example — App that reads ConfigMaps:</strong><br><pre># 1. Create ServiceAccount\napiVersion: v1\nkind: ServiceAccount\nmetadata:\n  name: config-reader\n  namespace: production\n\n# 2. Create Role\napiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1\nkind: Role\nmetadata:\n  name: configmap-reader\n  namespace: production\nrules:\n- apiGroups: [\"\"]\n  resources: [\"configmaps\"]\n  verbs: [\"get\", \"list\"]\n\n# 3. Bind Role to ServiceAccount\napiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1\nkind: RoleBinding\nmetadata:\n  name: read-configmaps\n  namespace: production\nsubjects:\n- kind: ServiceAccount\n  name: config-reader\n  namespace: production\nroleRef:\n  kind: Role\n  name: configmap-reader\n  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io\n\n# 4. Pod uses ServiceAccount\nspec:\n  serviceAccountName: config-reader</pre><br><strong>Debugging RBAC:</strong><br><pre># Check if user can perform action\nkubectl auth can-i create pods --namespace production\n\n# Check what a ServiceAccount can do\nkubectl auth can-i --list --as=system:serviceaccount:production:config-reader</pre>"},

    {q:"What happens during a pod eviction due to resource pressure?",d:"hard",id:"happens-during-pod-eviction",
     a:"<strong>Node pressure eviction</strong> occurs when a node runs out of resources (memory, disk, PIDs). The kubelet proactively evicts Pods to reclaim resources and prevent node instability.<br><br><strong>Eviction signals (node conditions):</strong><ul><li><code>MemoryPressure</code> — available memory < threshold</li><li><code>DiskPressure</code> — available disk < threshold</li><li><code>PIDPressure</code> — available PIDs < threshold</li></ul><br><strong>Default thresholds:</strong><br><pre>memory.available < 100Mi\nnodefs.available < 10%  # root filesystem\nimagefs.available < 15%  # container images/writable layers</pre><br><strong>Eviction process:</strong><ol><li><strong>Soft eviction:</strong> grace period (e.g., 1 minute) before evicting</li><li><strong>Hard eviction:</strong> immediate eviction when threshold crossed</li><li><strong>Pod selection order (lowest to highest priority):</strong><ul><li><strong>BestEffort Pods</strong> (no resource requests/limits) — evicted first</li><li><strong>Burstable Pods</strong> (requests < limits) — evicted next, ordered by usage exceeding requests</li><li><strong>Guaranteed Pods</strong> (requests = limits) — evicted last</li></ul></li><li>kubelet sends SIGTERM → waits for <code>terminationGracePeriodSeconds</code> (default 30s) → SIGKILL</li><li>Pod status becomes <code>Failed</code> with reason <code>Evicted</code></li></ol><br><strong>QoS Classes (quality of service):</strong><br><br><strong>Guaranteed:</strong> all containers have CPU and memory requests = limits<br><pre>resources:\n  requests:\n    memory: \"1Gi\"\n    cpu: \"500m\"\n  limits:\n    memory: \"1Gi\"\n    cpu: \"500m\"</pre><br><strong>Burstable:</strong> at least one container has requests < limits<br><pre>resources:\n  requests:\n    memory: \"512Mi\"\n  limits:\n    memory: \"1Gi\"</pre><br><strong>BestEffort:</strong> no requests or limits specified (highest eviction priority)<br><br><strong>Preventing evictions:</strong><ul><li>Set appropriate resource requests and limits</li><li>Use <code>PriorityClass</code> for critical workloads</li><li>Monitor node resource usage with Prometheus</li><li>Use Pod Disruption Budgets (PDB) to limit voluntary disruptions</li></ul><br><strong>Checking evicted Pods:</strong><br><pre>kubectl get pods --field-selector=status.phase=Failed</pre>"},

    {q:"What is a Helm chart and why would you use it?",d:"medium",id:"helm-chart-would-you",
     a:"<strong>Helm</strong> is a package manager for Kubernetes that bundles multiple Kubernetes manifests into a single <strong>chart</strong>, making it easier to deploy, upgrade, and manage applications.<br><br><strong>What is a Helm chart?</strong><ul><li>A collection of YAML templates (Deployment, Service, Ingress, etc.)</li><li>A <code>values.yaml</code> file with default configuration</li><li>A <code>Chart.yaml</code> file with metadata</li><li>Versioned and shareable (e.g., via Helm Hub, Artifact Hub)</li></ul><br><strong>Chart structure:</strong><br><pre>mychart/\n  Chart.yaml          # metadata (name, version, description)\n  values.yaml         # default configuration values\n  templates/          # Kubernetes manifest templates\n    deployment.yaml\n    service.yaml\n    ingress.yaml\n  charts/             # dependency charts</pre><br><strong>Why use Helm?</strong><ol><li><strong>Templating:</strong> reuse manifests with different values (dev/staging/prod)</li><li><strong>Versioning:</strong> rollback to previous chart versions</li><li><strong>Dependency management:</strong> charts can depend on other charts (e.g., app + PostgreSQL)</li><li><strong>Release management:</strong> track deployments as \"releases\"</li><li><strong>Sharing:</strong> public charts for common software (PostgreSQL, Redis, NGINX)</li></ol><br><strong>Installing a chart:</strong><br><pre># Add a chart repository\nhelm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami\n\n# Install PostgreSQL\nhelm install my-postgres bitnami/postgresql\n\n# Install with custom values\nhelm install my-app ./mychart --values prod-values.yaml</pre><br><strong>Example template (deployment.yaml):</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: {{ .Values.name }}\nspec:\n  replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }}\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: {{ .Values.name }}\n        image: {{ .Values.image.repository }}:{{ .Values.image.tag }}\n        ports:\n        - containerPort: {{ .Values.service.port }}</pre><br><strong>values.yaml:</strong><br><pre>name: myapp\nreplicaCount: 3\nimage:\n  repository: myapp\n  tag: 1.0.0\nservice:\n  port: 8080</pre><br><strong>Helm commands:</strong><br><pre>helm list                  # list installed releases\nhelm upgrade my-app ./mychart  # upgrade a release\nhelm rollback my-app 1     # rollback to revision 1\nhelm uninstall my-app      # delete a release</pre><br><strong>Alternative — Kustomize:</strong> simpler, no templating, uses overlays. Good for straightforward use cases."},

    {q:"What is a Job in Kubernetes and how does it differ from a CronJob?",d:"easy",id:"job-kubernetes-it-differ",
     a:"<strong>Job</strong> and <strong>CronJob</strong> are for running tasks that terminate (batch processing, ETL, backups), unlike Deployments which run continuously.<br><br><strong>Job:</strong><ul><li>Runs Pods until they successfully complete (exit code 0)</li><li>Restarts Pods if they fail (configurable)</li><li>Use for: one-time tasks, data migrations, batch processing</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Database migration Job:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: batch/v1\nkind: Job\nmetadata:\n  name: db-migration\nspec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: migrate\n        image: flyway/flyway:9\n        command: [\"flyway\", \"migrate\"]\n      restartPolicy: Never  # or OnFailure\n  backoffLimit: 3  # retry up to 3 times</pre><br><strong>Parallelism and completion:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  completions: 5     # run 5 successful Pods total\n  parallelism: 2     # run 2 Pods at a time</pre><br><strong>CronJob:</strong><ul><li>Runs Jobs on a <em>schedule</em> (cron syntax)</li><li>Use for: periodic backups, report generation, data cleanup</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Daily backup CronJob:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: batch/v1\nkind: CronJob\nmetadata:\n  name: backup\nspec:\n  schedule: \"0 2 * * *\"  # 2 AM daily\n  jobTemplate:\n    spec:\n      template:\n        spec:\n          containers:\n          - name: backup\n            image: postgres:15\n            command: [\"pg_dump\", \"-U\", \"postgres\", \"> /backup/dump.sql\"]\n          restartPolicy: OnFailure</pre><br><strong>Cron syntax:</strong><br><pre>* * * * *\n│ │ │ │ │\n│ │ │ │ └─── day of week (0-7, 0 and 7 = Sunday)\n│ │ │ └───── month (1-12)\n│ │ └─────── day of month (1-31)\n│ └───────── hour (0-23)\n└─────────── minute (0-59)</pre><br><strong>CronJob options:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  concurrencyPolicy: Forbid  # Allow, Forbid, or Replace\n  successfulJobsHistoryLimit: 3\n  failedJobsHistoryLimit: 1\n  startingDeadlineSeconds: 300  # if missed by > 5min, skip</pre><br><strong>Cleanup:</strong> Jobs don't auto-delete. Set <code>ttlSecondsAfterFinished: 100</code> to auto-clean completed Jobs."},

    {q:"How do you debug a Pod that is in CrashLoopBackOff state?",d:"hard",id:"you-debug-pod-that",
     a:"<strong>CrashLoopBackOff</strong> means the container repeatedly crashes and Kubernetes is backing off before restarting it again (delay increases exponentially: 10s → 20s → 40s → max 5min).<br><br><strong>Debugging steps:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Check Pod status and events:</strong><br><pre>kubectl describe pod &lt;pod-name&gt;</pre>Look for:<ul><li><code>State</code> and <code>Last State</code> (exit code)</li><li><code>Events</code> section (image pull errors, OOM kills, liveness probe failures)</li></ul><br><strong>2. Check container logs:</strong><br><pre># Current logs\nkubectl logs &lt;pod-name&gt;\n\n# Previous logs (from crashed container)\nkubectl logs &lt;pod-name&gt; --previous</pre><br><strong>3. Common causes and fixes:</strong><br><br><strong>Application crash (exit code 1):</strong><ul><li>Check logs for exceptions (NullPointerException, ClassNotFoundException)</li><li>Missing environment variables or config</li><li>Database connection failure</li></ul><br><strong>OOM Killed (exit code 137):</strong><br><pre>State:          Terminated\n  Reason:       OOMKilled</pre>Fix: increase memory limit:<br><pre>resources:\n  limits:\n    memory: \"2Gi\"</pre><br><strong>Image pull error:</strong><br><pre>Failed to pull image \"myapp:1.0\": rpc error: code = Unknown desc = Error response from daemon: pull access denied</pre>Fix: check image name, tag, and registry credentials (imagePullSecrets).<br><br><strong>Liveness probe failure:</strong><br>Pod starts, then liveness probe fails → Pod killed → repeat<br><pre>Liveness probe failed: HTTP probe failed with statuscode: 500</pre>Fix: increase <code>initialDelaySeconds</code> or fix the health check endpoint.<br><br><strong>Missing dependencies:</strong> App starts before database is ready<br>Fix: add <code>initContainer</code> or readiness probe dependencies.<br><br><strong>Exit code 0 (successful exit):</strong> App finishes and exits<br>Fix: use a Job instead of a Deployment, or keep app running (e.g., <code>tail -f /dev/null</code> for debugging).<br><br><strong>4. Interactive debugging:</strong><br><pre># Run a debug container in the Pod (Kubernetes 1.23+)\nkubectl debug &lt;pod-name&gt; -it --image=busybox --target=&lt;container-name&gt;\n\n# Or exec into a running container (if it stays up long enough)\nkubectl exec -it &lt;pod-name&gt; -- /bin/sh</pre><br><strong>5. Check resource limits:</strong><br><pre>kubectl top pod &lt;pod-name&gt;</pre>If CPU is throttled or memory is near limit, increase resources.<br><br><strong>6. Check Node conditions:</strong><br><pre>kubectl describe node &lt;node-name&gt;</pre>Look for MemoryPressure, DiskPressure, or node issues."},

    {q:"What is a Network Policy and how does it control Pod traffic?",d:"hard",id:"network-policy-it-control",
     a:"<strong>NetworkPolicy</strong> defines rules for how Pods can communicate with each other and with external endpoints. By default, Kubernetes allows all traffic — NetworkPolicies enforce <em>deny-by-default</em> segmentation.<br><br><strong>Requires a CNI plugin that supports NetworkPolicy:</strong> Calico, Cilium, Weave Net (NOT flannel or basic kubenet).<br><br><strong>Three types of traffic:</strong><ol><li><strong>Ingress:</strong> incoming traffic to a Pod</li><li><strong>Egress:</strong> outgoing traffic from a Pod</li><li><strong>Default behavior:</strong> if no NetworkPolicy selects a Pod, all traffic is allowed</li></ol><br><strong>Example — Allow only frontend to backend:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1\nkind: NetworkPolicy\nmetadata:\n  name: backend-policy\n  namespace: production\nspec:\n  podSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: backend\n  policyTypes:\n  - Ingress\n  ingress:\n  - from:\n    - podSelector:\n        matchLabels:\n          app: frontend\n    ports:\n    - protocol: TCP\n      port: 8080</pre>This policy:<ul><li>Applies to Pods with <code>app=backend</code></li><li>Allows ingress only from Pods with <code>app=frontend</code> on port 8080</li><li>Blocks all other ingress traffic</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Block all ingress (default deny):</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1\nkind: NetworkPolicy\nmetadata:\n  name: deny-all\nspec:\n  podSelector: {}  # matches all Pods\n  policyTypes:\n  - Ingress</pre><br><strong>Example — Allow egress to database only:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1\nkind: NetworkPolicy\nmetadata:\n  name: app-egress\nspec:\n  podSelector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: myapp\n  policyTypes:\n  - Egress\n  egress:\n  - to:\n    - podSelector:\n        matchLabels:\n          app: postgres\n    ports:\n    - protocol: TCP\n      port: 5432\n  - to:  # Allow DNS\n    - namespaceSelector:\n        matchLabels:\n          name: kube-system\n    ports:\n    - protocol: UDP\n      port: 53</pre><br><strong>Selectors:</strong><ul><li><code>podSelector</code> — select Pods by labels</li><li><code>namespaceSelector</code> — select Pods in namespaces by labels</li><li><code>ipBlock</code> — select external IPs (CIDR ranges)</li></ul><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Start with default-deny policies per namespace</li><li>Explicitly allow required traffic</li><li>Remember to allow DNS (kube-dns/CoreDNS on port 53 UDP)</li><li>Use namespace labels for cross-namespace communication</li></ul><br><strong>Debugging:</strong> If traffic is blocked unexpectedly, check NetworkPolicies:<br><pre>kubectl get networkpolicies -A\nkubectl describe networkpolicy &lt;name&gt;</pre>"},

    {q:"What are Init Containers and when would you use them?",d:"medium",id:"init-containers-would-you",
     a:"<strong>Init Containers</strong> are specialized containers that run <em>before</em> the main application containers start. They run to completion sequentially, and the main containers only start after all init containers succeed.<br><br><strong>Use cases:</strong><ol><li><strong>Wait for dependencies:</strong> wait for database, Redis, or external service to be ready</li><li><strong>Setup tasks:</strong> clone a Git repo, download config files, run database migrations</li><li><strong>Security:</strong> run privileged setup tasks separately from the app container</li><li><strong>Pre-populate volumes:</strong> copy static files into a shared volume</li></ol><br><strong>Key differences from regular containers:</strong><ul><li>Always run to completion (exit) before app containers start</li><li>Run sequentially in the order defined</li><li>If an init container fails → Pod status is <code>Init:Error</code> or <code>Init:CrashLoopBackOff</code></li><li>Don't support liveness/readiness/startup probes</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Wait for database:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nmetadata:\n  name: myapp\nspec:\n  initContainers:\n  - name: wait-for-db\n    image: busybox:1.35\n    command: ['sh', '-c', 'until nc -z postgres 5432; do echo waiting for db; sleep 2; done']\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0</pre><br><strong>Example — Clone Git repo into volume:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  initContainers:\n  - name: git-clone\n    image: alpine/git:latest\n    command: ['git', 'clone', 'https://github.com/user/repo.git', '/data']\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: shared-data\n      mountPath: /data\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: shared-data\n      mountPath: /app/data\n  volumes:\n  - name: shared-data\n    emptyDir: {}</pre><br><strong>Example — Run database migration:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  initContainers:\n  - name: db-migration\n    image: flyway/flyway:9\n    command: ['flyway', 'migrate']\n    env:\n    - name: DB_URL\n      value: \"jdbc:postgresql://postgres:5432/mydb\"</pre><br><strong>Multiple init containers:</strong> Run sequentially:<br><pre>spec:\n  initContainers:\n  - name: init-1\n    image: busybox\n    command: ['sh', '-c', 'echo init-1 && sleep 5']\n  - name: init-2\n    image: busybox\n    command: ['sh', '-c', 'echo init-2 && sleep 5']</pre><br><strong>Debugging init containers:</strong><br><pre>kubectl describe pod &lt;pod-name&gt;\nkubectl logs &lt;pod-name&gt; -c &lt;init-container-name&gt;</pre>"},

    {q:"What is a sidecar pattern and what are common use cases in Kubernetes?",d:"medium",id:"sidecar-pattern-common-use",
     a:"The <strong>sidecar pattern</strong> deploys a helper container alongside the main application container in the same Pod. They share the same lifecycle, network, and storage.<br><br><strong>Common use cases:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Log shipping:</strong> sidecar collects logs and sends to centralized logging (Fluentd, Filebeat)<br><pre>spec:\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: logs\n      mountPath: /var/log/app\n  - name: log-shipper\n    image: fluent/fluentd:v1.14\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: logs\n      mountPath: /var/log/app\n  volumes:\n  - name: logs\n    emptyDir: {}</pre><br><strong>2. Service mesh (Envoy proxy):</strong> Istio, Linkerd inject a sidecar proxy for traffic management, observability, security<br><pre>spec:\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0\n  - name: envoy-proxy\n    image: envoyproxy/envoy:v1.25\n    # Intercepts all traffic in/out of the Pod</pre><br><strong>3. Metrics exporter:</strong> export app metrics to Prometheus<br><pre>spec:\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    image: myapp:1.0\n  - name: metrics-exporter\n    image: prom/statsd-exporter:v0.22.0\n    ports:\n    - containerPort: 9102</pre><br><strong>4. Configuration hot-reload:</strong> sidecar watches ConfigMap changes and reloads app config<br><br><strong>5. Security proxy:</strong> sidecar enforces mTLS, authentication, or authorization<br><br><strong>6. Adapter pattern:</strong> normalize data format (e.g., legacy metrics → Prometheus format)<br><br><strong>Characteristics:</strong><ul><li>Sidecar and main container start together</li><li>Share the same Pod IP (communicate via <code>localhost</code>)</li><li>Share volumes for data exchange</li><li>If main container crashes, sidecar keeps running (and vice versa)</li></ul><br><strong>Service mesh automatic injection:</strong><br>Istio and Linkerd automatically inject sidecar proxies via mutating webhooks:<br><pre>kubectl label namespace production istio-injection=enabled</pre>Now all Pods in <code>production</code> namespace get an Envoy sidecar automatically.<br><br><strong>When NOT to use sidecars:</strong><ul><li>If the helper logic can be a library or agent inside the main container</li><li>If it significantly increases resource usage</li><li>If it complicates debugging and lifecycle management</li></ul>"},

    {q:"How do you implement resource quotas and limit ranges in Kubernetes?",d:"medium",id:"you-implement-resource-quotas",
     a:"<strong>ResourceQuota</strong> and <strong>LimitRange</strong> enforce resource consumption limits at the namespace level to prevent resource exhaustion and ensure fair sharing.<br><br><strong>ResourceQuota:</strong> limits <em>total</em> resources consumed by all Pods in a namespace.<br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: ResourceQuota\nmetadata:\n  name: compute-quota\n  namespace: dev\nspec:\n  hard:\n    requests.cpu: \"10\"          # total CPU requests\n    requests.memory: 20Gi       # total memory requests\n    limits.cpu: \"20\"            # total CPU limits\n    limits.memory: 40Gi         # total memory limits\n    persistentvolumeclaims: \"5\" # max 5 PVCs\n    services.loadbalancers: \"2\" # max 2 LoadBalancer Services</pre><br><strong>Object count quotas:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  hard:\n    pods: \"50\"\n    services: \"20\"\n    secrets: \"10\"\n    configmaps: \"10\"</pre><br><strong>Storage quotas:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  hard:\n    requests.storage: 100Gi\n    persistentvolumeclaims: \"10\"</pre><br><strong>Checking quota usage:</strong><br><pre>kubectl describe resourcequota compute-quota -n dev</pre><br><strong>LimitRange:</strong> sets <em>default</em> and <em>min/max</em> resource limits for individual Pods/containers.<br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: LimitRange\nmetadata:\n  name: limit-range\n  namespace: dev\nspec:\n  limits:\n  - max:            # maximum per container\n      cpu: \"2\"\n      memory: 2Gi\n    min:            # minimum per container\n      cpu: \"100m\"\n      memory: 128Mi\n    default:        # default limit if not specified\n      cpu: \"500m\"\n      memory: 512Mi\n    defaultRequest: # default request if not specified\n      cpu: \"200m\"\n      memory: 256Mi\n    type: Container</pre><br><strong>Pod-level LimitRange:</strong><br><pre>  - max:\n      cpu: \"4\"\n      memory: 4Gi\n    type: Pod</pre><br><strong>PVC LimitRange:</strong><br><pre>  - max:\n      storage: 10Gi\n    min:\n      storage: 1Gi\n    type: PersistentVolumeClaim</pre><br><strong>Enforcement:</strong><ul><li>If a Pod exceeds a LimitRange, it's rejected at creation time</li><li>If total namespace usage exceeds a ResourceQuota, new resource creation is blocked</li></ul><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Always set ResourceQuotas in multi-tenant clusters</li><li>Use LimitRanges to enforce defaults and prevent unbounded resource requests</li><li>Monitor quota usage with Prometheus and alert when close to limits</li><li>Set quotas per team/project namespace</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is a Service Mesh and how does it enhance microservices communication?",d:"medium",id:"service-mesh-it-enhance",
     a:"A <strong>Service Mesh</strong> is an infrastructure layer that handles service-to-service communication, providing observability, security, and reliability features without changing application code.<br><br><strong>Popular service meshes:</strong> Istio, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh<br><br><strong>How it works:</strong><ul><li>Injects a <strong>sidecar proxy</strong> (Envoy, Linkerd-proxy) into every Pod</li><li>All traffic flows through the proxy</li><li>Control plane configures proxies centrally</li></ul><br><strong>Key features:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Traffic Management:</strong><ul><li>Intelligent load balancing (round-robin, least connections, random)</li><li>Traffic splitting (A/B testing, canary deployments)</li><li>Circuit breaking and retries</li><li>Timeouts and fault injection for chaos testing</li></ul><br><strong>2. Security:</strong><ul><li>Automatic mTLS (mutual TLS) between services</li><li>Certificate rotation</li><li>Authorization policies</li></ul><br><strong>3. Observability:</strong><ul><li>Distributed tracing (Jaeger, Zipkin integration)</li><li>Metrics (request rate, latency, error rate)</li><li>Service topology visualization (Kiali for Istio)</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Istio traffic splitting (canary):</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: networking.istio.io/v1beta1\nkind: VirtualService\nmetadata:\n  name: reviews\nspec:\n  hosts:\n  - reviews\n  http:\n  - match:\n    - headers:\n        user:\n          exact: \"beta-tester\"\n    route:\n    - destination:\n        host: reviews\n        subset: v2\n  - route:\n    - destination:\n        host: reviews\n        subset: v1\n      weight: 90\n    - destination:\n        host: reviews\n        subset: v2\n      weight: 10</pre>90% of traffic goes to v1, 10% to v2 (canary). Beta testers always get v2.<br><br><strong>Example — mTLS enforcement:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: security.istio.io/v1beta1\nkind: PeerAuthentication\nmetadata:\n  name: default\n  namespace: production\nspec:\n  mtls:\n    mode: STRICT</pre>All services in <code>production</code> namespace now require mTLS.<br><br><strong>When to use a service mesh:</strong><ul><li>Microservices architecture (10+ services)</li><li>Need for mTLS without code changes</li><li>Complex traffic management (A/B testing, canary)</li><li>Centralized observability</li></ul><br><strong>When NOT to use:</strong><ul><li>Simple monolith or &lt;5 services</li><li>Significant resource overhead (sidecar per Pod)</li><li>Added complexity in debugging</li></ul><br><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Application-level libraries (Resilience4j, Hystrix) or API gateways (Kong, NGINX)."},

    {q:"How do you handle database migrations in Kubernetes deployments?",d:"hard",id:"you-handle-database-migrations",
     a:"Database migrations in Kubernetes require careful coordination to avoid downtime, data corruption, or schema/application version mismatches.<br><br><strong>Common approaches:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Init Container (recommended for most cases):</strong><br>Run migration as an init container before the app starts:<br><pre>apiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: myapp\nspec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      initContainers:\n      - name: db-migration\n        image: flyway/flyway:9\n        command: ['flyway', 'migrate']\n        env:\n        - name: FLYWAY_URL\n          value: \"jdbc:postgresql://postgres:5432/mydb\"\n        - name: FLYWAY_USER\n          valueFrom:\n            secretKeyRef:\n              name: db-secret\n              key: username\n      containers:\n      - name: app\n        image: myapp:1.0</pre><strong>Pros:</strong> simple, automatic, migrations run before app<br><strong>Cons:</strong> all replicas run migration (use locking), delays startup<br><br><strong>2. Kubernetes Job (best for complex migrations):</strong><br>Run migration as a separate Job before deploying the app:<br><pre>apiVersion: batch/v1\nkind: Job\nmetadata:\n  name: db-migration-v2\nspec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: migrate\n        image: myapp:2.0\n        command: ['npm', 'run', 'migrate']\n      restartPolicy: OnFailure\n  backoffLimit: 3</pre>Deploy with:<br><pre>kubectl apply -f migration-job.yaml\nkubectl wait --for=condition=complete job/db-migration-v2 --timeout=300s\nkubectl apply -f app-deployment.yaml</pre><strong>Pros:</strong> explicit control, runs once, separates concerns<br><strong>Cons:</strong> manual orchestration (CI/CD pipeline step)<br><br><strong>3. Helm pre-install hook:</strong><br>Run migration before Helm install/upgrade:<br><pre>apiVersion: batch/v1\nkind: Job\nmetadata:\n  name: db-migration\n  annotations:\n    \"helm.sh/hook\": pre-install,pre-upgrade\n    \"helm.sh/hook-weight\": \"-5\"\n    \"helm.sh/hook-delete-policy\": before-hook-creation</pre><strong>Pros:</strong> integrated with Helm lifecycle<br><strong>Cons:</strong> Helm-specific<br><br><strong>4. Blue-Green deployment with backward-compatible migrations:</strong><br>Deploy new version alongside old, migrate, switch traffic:<ol><li>Write <strong>backward-compatible</strong> migrations (additive only)</li><li>Deploy new app version (both versions run simultaneously)</li><li>Run migration (safe because both versions work with new schema)</li><li>Switch traffic to new version</li><li>Remove old version</li></ol><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li><strong>Idempotency:</strong> migrations should be safe to run multiple times</li><li><strong>Locking:</strong> use advisory locks to prevent concurrent migrations</li><li><strong>Backward compatibility:</strong> avoid dropping columns/tables that old version needs</li><li><strong>Rollback plan:</strong> test rollback migrations in staging</li><li><strong>Schema versioning:</strong> use tools like Flyway, Liquibase, Alembic, django migrations</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Flyway with locking:</strong><br>Flyway has built-in locking via database table <code>flyway_schema_history</code>.<br><br><strong>Example — Advisory lock in PostgreSQL:</strong><br><pre>SELECT pg_advisory_lock(12345);\n-- run migrations\nSELECT pg_advisory_unlock(12345);</pre><br><strong>Rollback strategy:</strong><ul><li>Restore from backup (PostgreSQL: pg_dump)</li><li>Write down-migrations (rare in production)</li><li>Deploy old app version that works with new schema</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is Pod Disruption Budget (PDB) and why is it important?",d:"medium",id:"pod-disruption-budget-pdb",
     a:"A <strong>Pod Disruption Budget</strong> (PDB) limits the number of Pods that can be <em>voluntarily</em> disrupted (e.g., during node drains, cluster upgrades, or autoscaling) to ensure availability.<br><br><strong>Voluntary disruptions:</strong><ul><li>Node drain (<code>kubectl drain</code>)</li><li>Cluster autoscaling (removing nodes)</li><li>Node upgrades or reboots</li><li>Cluster admin actions</li></ul><br><strong>Involuntary disruptions:</strong> hardware failure, kernel panic, node running out of resources — PDB doesn't prevent these.<br><br><strong>Example — Ensure at least 2 replicas are always available:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: policy/v1\nkind: PodDisruptionBudget\nmetadata:\n  name: myapp-pdb\nspec:\n  minAvailable: 2\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: myapp</pre><br><strong>Example — Allow at most 1 Pod to be unavailable:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: policy/v1\nkind: PodDisruptionBudget\nmetadata:\n  name: myapp-pdb\nspec:\n  maxUnavailable: 1\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: myapp</pre><br><strong>Percentage-based:</strong><br><pre>spec:\n  maxUnavailable: \"30%\"  # allow 30% of Pods to be disrupted</pre><br><strong>How it works:</strong><ol><li>Admin runs <code>kubectl drain node1</code></li><li>Kubernetes checks PDB for each Pod on node1</li><li>If evicting a Pod would violate PDB (e.g., reduce available Pods below <code>minAvailable</code>), eviction is blocked</li><li>Node drain waits until PDB allows eviction (e.g., another replica becomes ready elsewhere)</li></ol><br><strong>Example scenario:</strong><ul><li>Deployment: 3 replicas of <code>myapp</code></li><li>PDB: <code>minAvailable: 2</code></li><li>Node drain starts</li><li>Kubernetes evicts 1 Pod → 2 remain → PDB satisfied</li><li>Tries to evict 2nd Pod → would leave only 1 → PDB blocks eviction</li><li>Waits for new replica to start on another node → 3 replicas again → evicts 2nd Pod</li></ul><br><strong>When PDB is critical:</strong><ul><li>Databases (maintain quorum for availability)</li><li>Stateful applications (avoid data unavailability)</li><li>High-availability services (SLO requirements)</li></ul><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Set PDB for all production Deployments/StatefulSets</li><li>For 3 replicas: <code>minAvailable: 2</code> or <code>maxUnavailable: 1</code></li><li>For single-replica: <code>minAvailable: 1</code> (blocks drains — use for critical services)</li><li>Don't set <code>minAvailable</code> = replica count (blocks all voluntary disruptions)</li></ul><br><strong>Checking PDB status:</strong><br><pre>kubectl get pdb\nkubectl describe pdb myapp-pdb</pre>"}
  ]
};
